<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Brenye Dyersbane</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Just Wondering but how does a cleric get to lvl 56 while being a Moron? i was grouped in Karnors last night on my bard and OMG was our cleric stupid get this she tried to Compleate Heal my bard. A Bard! of corse i died and right after our groups enchanter died why you ask thats right the cleric tried to Compleate heal the enchanter you would think by lvl 56 (how she got there i dont know pity groups maybe?) she would know not to do so go fig /shrug i would like to call attn to this for those clerics out there who dont have Compleate heal yet or just got it Compleate heal is for Warriors ONLY (minus Gnome, Wood Elf, and Hummies) at least in my opinion its a waste of mana and probably means death to those you are casting on i personaly dont use Compleate Heal unless the person has 3k hp or more if your not sure on hp do like i do buff everyone then ask what their hp are if you dont think you can remember it write it down (has a dry erase board next to comp for when on loot detail etc) it will help keep you from over healing (not that over healing is so bad is better then under healing ;p but the more mana you have the more you kill the faster you lvl) as well as let you know what heals to use  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"> just my two cp <P><BR>Brenye Dyersbane 51 Vicar Aro<BR>Sepientia Eveningmist 49 Cleric Tunare</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Rizena Halcyon</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><BR>I'm going to have to disagree with you here.  Complete heal should be used for Warriors of all races, Paladins, and Shadowknights.  Once you need to heal more than 1329 hps, complete heal is more efficient than Celestial Healing.<P>Pure casters receive always Remedy. Other melees usually do well with Celestial/Remedy if they can manage their aggro correctly, and there's a tank in the group to absorb the majority of the damage.<P>Rizena Halcyon<BR>Templar of the Mithril Tower<BR>Ayonae Ro</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Selene_Soulbinder</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I also disagree with the first poster.  I've found in my time as a cleric that the words always, never, and only just dont apply.<P>Your going to run into situations where the "rules" change.  Clerics often have to make many quick judgement calls on who's going to get that heal, how much and why.<P>Exprance in all kinds of situations is the best teacher on how to handle these times.  This is where the "power-leveled" cleric suffers.<P>Perhaps that's what you got.. perhaps not.  But just becuse you or someone else in your party died doesn't automaticaly make the cleric a bad one... nor does the fact that they didn't play as you thought they should.  <P>There are many diffrent cleric styles out there just as there are for other classes as well.  <BR>  </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gello</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I've CH'ed enchanters before during battle.  Never had one die while casting it.  Buffed to the gills they easily break 3k hp.  Even if they have just 2k hp's CH is easily the most efficient heal to use on them.  It just takes some awareness of what's going on, foresight into how well a situation is under control, and of course timing.<P>The worst clerics imho are the ones that go through their EQ life with no awareness of situation.  <I>All</I> spells are situational.  If you only heal by rote and never take the circumstances into consideration, you will be an awful cleric.  You'll never be the cleric that can make a group do the impossible.  You'll only be marginally better than a druid but without ports and snare.<P>That cleric's problem was simple misjudgement and/or bad timing.  Your problem as a cleric is that 'ONLY' word.  Timing and judgement can be refined over time.  Stubborn ignorance of circumstances is not so easy to cure.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Selinar Crystalwind</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The thing that can't be overlooked is the masive efficency of a Complete Heal.  Something that in my mind that good clerics look at with regard to when to cast what isn't just how many HP someone has, but the Rate of Damage.  If someone is losing HP very rapidly, you drop either a Remedy or a Divine Light on them.  If it's a slow progression, you do a CHeal, and you an mop up or stabilize with Celestial.<P>For instance, we have a monk pulling on a raid.  She's FD'd after a pull and at 2 bubbles of health, and stable.  I could Celestial her, bring her up to 4 bubbles and say good enough, or I can hit her with a Remedy to top her off as you should on pullers.  However, since she was stable, why not cast a complete heal?  You aren't in danger of having her die, and she can be up and ready to pull in 10 seconds, as opposed to 4.5+24+3+ decision and thinking time.<P>Alternatively, if I have a SK and a ranger in my group, and they are slowly losing HP in a fight, and I feel that the fight is well controlled and the risks mitigated, then you bet I'm going to wait to CHeal them.  On the other hand, it they are mezzed mobs or casters, or the possibility of adds, I'll toss a Celestial at them a lot earlier, knowing that things could get bad with little warning.<P>Obviously though, they are set rules as well.  Chanters get a Remedy at the first HP loss.  Chanters can lose SO many HP in 3.5 seconds it's sick - sometimes if I have the mana and the chanter is AOE mezzing, I'll hit them with a celestial just as the pull comes in, even though they are at full health.  On the flip side, if things are controlled, I may let my tank get down to under a bubble before I even start a CHeal, particually if I'm low on mana.  <P>Being a good cleric is a lot more than 'cheal the tank at 2 bubbles, remedy casters, celestial everyone else'.  It's a combination of mana control, knowing and estimating rate of damage, analysis of the potential danger in your current combat, awareness of what might be roaming toward you from around the corner, and in case of really good clerics, proactively helping chanters with stuns and nukes to boot.<P>A robo-cleric can get very boring, and you can slip by to high levels just by watching those red bars.  A well-played cleric on the other hand as every bit the situation awareness of an enchanter, and is almost as busy.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">electrae</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Can't quite imagine using cheal on a chanter...  I've never had a chanter last 10 seconds when they were getting beaten on.  But perhaps when I'm level 60 that will be different.<P>Selinar state it very well.  It is all situational.  Sometimes it can be very risky even chealing a tank... just depends on what the rest of the group is doing, how under control the fight is and many, many other things.<P>But sure, I complete heal all kinds of tanks all the time at my level.  When folks start getting 2500-3000+ hit points it makes sense and you often have plenty of time to cast it.<P>And rangers just loooove to be completely healed, makes them feel like BIG tanks.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Marrs</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Just to chuck in my 2cp. When I am fighting in groups, I always have CHeal, Celest Heal and Remedy memmed. CHeal for Wars, Pallys, SKs and usually Rangers. Celest for Bards, and sometimes Rangers depending on the buffs. Remedy on Casters and sometimes Bards, again dependsing on the buffs. I just find when it comes to CHeal that its still really hard to time on anyone with low HP. It just takes ages to get the spell off so has to be timed with great precision, where it is a great deal easier on Wars, Pallys, SKs and Rangers. I can however agree that if my casters have more then 3K worth of HP then it would be much more mana efficient to use CHeal instead, but I have never been in that situation. As I said timing is everything with healing of any type and you just have to get used to it, and yes PLed clerics have a disadvantage where that is concerned as they have not had the opportunity to get group exp. This is just MHO so take as you wish. But I have never failed using this method of healing.<P>------------------<BR>Marrs Pureheart <BR>52 Vicar<BR>The Tribunal Server<P>"May the power of Tunare guide you in your journeys"</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tundar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">A fully buffed bard can easily have around 2500-3000 hp or more and if you take the rate of damage dealt into consideration, CH sould be just as good (perhaps even better) a solution as cel heal.<P>I CH pallys, monks, rangers, and sk's and of course; warriors. Depending on the situation I even CH the odd rogue.<P>Don't blame a cleric for trying his best, you might even learn something  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>CH on a chanter? Heh, never tried that, do cel heal quite often, but never CH  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aiien</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I use complete healing on all classes all the time, you just have to be very aware of aggro, and your group has to trust you and work with you to make sure you pull it off.<P>I find remedy heals an insignifigant amount, especially on anything but a wizard or a mage. Divine light is a nice heal, but a terrible spell, it still fizzles too much and it's frighteningly inefficient. Celestial is nice during downtime and to heal someone who isn't aggro'd and doesn't merit a cheal, but it's too slow to be a good combat heal most of the time.<P>Generally, the only heal spells I use are cheal and heroic bond. I'll also use remedy when I don't have time for a cheal, but people I group with are pretty good at managing aggro, most of the time. I keep celestial memmed for those annoying situations where you really want to cheal two different party members, but only have time to cheal one safely.<P>Aiien.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dolfar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">WOW! all i got to say is that if you let your Chanter go down nuff to where you got to C heal them, you got problems and should prolly invest your time in another class. Even a Chanter with 3k hp its not worth C healing cuz he dont have the ac he might as well have 1k hp. I'm sorry I never have and can say I will most likely never C heal a caster. Rem + Cel heal = same mana as 1 c heal and its alot faster, and will keep your chanter alive, then have him die when your almost 1/2 way threw C heal.<P>Dolfar Harkon<BR>-55th Priest of Innoruuk-<BR>Veeshan Guard<BR>Cazic</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gello</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">hehe it's a different game for different people.  I've been put into mostly enchanter groups at raids for months.  They don't die in my group, I make sure of that.  They never panic either, some even request me for their group.  The enchanters I work with are top class.  Each of us are confident in the others' ability so we work well as a unit.  If they spend a fraction of their attention on their own hp, then I feel I've failed.<P>That's not to say I always use ch when healing an enchanter.  I was giving an extreme case that some of us don't always use any spell in by-rote situations.  Maybe 2-3 times I've done it out of thousands of heals on enchanters. :P  The situations called for it.<P>I can do a world of healing with "10% gtg", I think my time invested as a cleric wasn't wasted.  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aerie</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Speaking from my cleric-who-plays-enchanter point of view:<P>-Say I am getting a CHeal from a cleric in a pick up group. Then I'd be <B>mortified.</B> It's a fairly good bet I would live through, provided I am not tanking some uber Velious mobs. (Enchanters get hit a lot, and they do pay a lot of attention to HP/AC gear.) I would still question the use of CHeal - because it's not something I normally would have done as a cleric.<P>-In the same situation, I am getting a CHeal from a cleric who I have known for long time to be an excellent cleric and generally has a good grasp of the situation. You can bet I would never question her choice of heal, even if her gamble doesn't pay off. Why? Because I think if I were in her shoes, I probably would have thought CHeal was the best spell to cast too.<P>Oh, and the key is to cast CHeal when they just start getting beat up, not when they are three bubbles down.  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/tongue.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Caleal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I use CH on enchanters a lot. The key thing is that I'm in a raiding guild and vs SoV stuff, the enchanter normally is only getting hit because of Tash. If the enchanter lives through the few hits from that, there is basicly nothing else the enchanter is going to be doing that will cause agro. At least this is true in ToV. <BR>So, if I have an enchanter thats buffed up to 3500-4000 hp and he gets smacked around for 2-3k damage in the couple of combat round he has agro, he better go stand around a corner out of the AE because I'm gona use CH on him. =)<P>------------------<BR>Caleal P`Terak<BR>BATTLE CLERIC of Innoruuk<BR>Cazic-Thule server<BR>Officer, Shadowed Soul</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dolfar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">But the time you waste on C healing a chanter, could mean another persons death. If you Cel heal wich will do the job, (keeping him alive) you have plenty of time to toss another heal out in the same amount of time. But its all vary true it all depends on the situation. I just have not been in a situation where i thought C healing a chanter sounded like a good idea... yet. Maby ill change my mind when the time comes. I'll let ya know.<P>Dolfar Harkon<BR>55th Priest of Innoruuk<BR>Veeshan Guard<BR>Cazic</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sydney</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Im a bit crazy when it comes to CH and getting 100% mana to healing ratio, by the time my CH kicks in the tank is at about 1/4 bubble of health left and Im still at 85% mana ready to kill the ghoul lord again etc.<P>Ive never ever lost a tank to bad timing on my CH, sometimes if I get halfway through a CH and luck goes the way of the monster I just duck to break casting then cast a quick heal then CH again. <P>Usually people in my groups die because a) Im getting hit and cant heal or b) Enchanter is mezzing the things that the tanks are fighting instead of the things that are killing me see a) above. Basically the enchanter must at all costs mez what is on the cleric , and like wise the cleric must help the chanter out as well.<P>I usually ask all casters to root any mezzed mobs before the monsters mez wears off.<P>Im still learning tho , and I haven't had the luck to have gotten Celetrial healing spell yet so I have to work closely with the groups enchanter.<P>A group with a good cleric and enchanter can make the impossible happen and get crazy exp.<P>Sydney Starr Lvl 45 Cleric<p>[This message has been edited by Sydney (edited 07-15-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gello</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Oh yeah the new ducking thing has improved CH *A LOT*.  In ToV last night I was aborting heals often to get them timed ever closer to 1hp hehe.  Start CH when tank is at 3.5 bubbles, if they lose aggro and stop at 2.2 bubbles, abort ch and be ready to start it on them once they take damage again.  Really a dramatic effect on mana usage.  (This is with 60 taunters vs drakes, wurms and wyverns in ToV, haven't perfected a way to maximize ch on those that get sudden stray aggro)<P>And because it makes people squirm I've ch'ed 2 enchanters this weekend. neener neener! :P  (Celestial heal is on page 30 of my spellbook if curious.  Celestial Elixir+Remedy costs more mana than a CH and won't heal as much.)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gimily</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dolfar is Exactly Correct in his postings.  He seems to be the most on the same page as I am.<P>Gimily Smashfist<BR>56 Cleric<BR>Quellious</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
